                        <h3>City of God</h3>
                        <p>The 2003 Miramax film "City of God," written by Braulino Mantovani and directed by Fernando Meirelles, based on actual events and the novel by Paolo Lin, is a coming of age story about a group of kids who struggle in the Brazilian ghetto. The film has been described as "dazzling."<sup>1</sup> It's "exploration of life in the gun-crazy, drug-addled Brazilian-slums. It is unflinchingly honest. The movie follows the children of Cidade de Deus as they struggle with childhood "devoid of fathers or hope, guns replace toys and drugs" are "the main currency of power."<sup>1</sup> "The violence...is extreme and shocking, even though there is virtually no blood. Part of the reason has to do with the age of the killers and their victims. Gang members are children. They kill and are killed with the same callousness as adults. Death is no respecter of age in the slums of Rio de Janeiro. The immediate goal of a seven-year-old homeless boy is not finding a family or a friend, but finding a gun." When "war...is declared, children are quick to declare their allegiance so they can obtain a weapon and go out to kill".<sup>2</sup> Children murder other children and later adults as they gain power and continue the cycle.</p>
                        <hr align="left" size="1">
                        <p><small>
                            <ul>
                                <li>1. Bernard D. McDonald, "God Zone," Pavement (August/September 2003): pp. 108-111.</li>
                                <li>2. <a href="https://www.reelviews.net/reelviews/city-of-god" target="_blank">James Berardinelli, City of God. (2003)</a></li>
                            </ul>
                            </small></p>
                        <p>&nbsp;</p>
                        <p>"City Of God" has many of the same character types and storylines as "Boyz 'R' Us." The level of violence that occurs without showing any blood makes "City Of God" an excellent source of comparison and inspiration for the type of movie that "Boyz 'R' Us" should be. The lack of bloodshed on-screen made the film a little difficult to view. When watching the movie for the first time, the editing and shooting style of the film allowed my imagination to get the better of me. By not showing anything, the story is more impactful and engages the audience.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
                <div class="jumbotron" id="griffith-red">
