                    <h3>Kids</h3>
                        <p>The 1995 Independent Pictures and Guys Upstairs film "Kids," written by Harmony Korine and directed by Larry Clark, depicts a stark world of skateboard-soaring, morally impaired teenagers in New York City whose parents are practically nonexistent, whose sexual activities are devoid of human concern, and whose thoughts of the future reach no further than to the night ahead.<sup>3</sup> The story follows a group of teenage boys and girls through one day and night, during which they travel Manhattan on skateboards and subway trains, have sex, drink, use drugs, talk, party, and crash in a familiar stupor, before starting all over again the next day. The movie sees this culture in such flat, unblinking detail that it feels like a documentary; it knows what it's talking about.<sup>4</sup></p>
                        <hr align="left" size="1">    
                        <p><small>
                             <ul>
                                <li>3. <a href="http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/style/longterm/movies/videos/kidsnrhowe_c02a2c.htm" target="_blank">Desson Howe, Kids. (1995).</li>
                                <li>4. <a href="http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/19950728/REVIEWS/507280301/1023" target="_blank">Roger Ebert, Kids. (1995).</li>
                            </ul>
                            </small></p>
                        <p>&nbsp;</p>
                        <p>"Kids" depicts the unflinching world of kids in New York. In "Boyz 'R' Us," Mitch almost comes from this world. While he is trying to escape this potential world, he is drawn to it. It's part of his past, and it's a past he is having trouble letting go of. The characters in "Kids" are uncaring and are only after the next thrill and underage fuck. While at this point, the kids in "Boyz 'R' Us" are not this brutal, they crave that level of excitement in their lives. The next generation of kids in "Boyz 'R' Us" wants so badly to be part of the world of "Kids." When and if they get, there is entirely up to them.</p>
                                 </div>
                </div>
            </div>
