                    <div class="container">
      			<div class="row">
        			<div class="col-md-6 col-md-offset-3" id="description">
                        <h3>Chopper</h3>
                        <p>"Chopper," the 2001 joint venture of Pariah, Mushroom Pictures, Cherub Pictures, and Films Finance Corporation Australia, written and directed by Andrew Dominik, is based on the experiences and universe of, and as described in Mark "Chopper" Read's book "From the Inside." His universe consists of "black teeth, paranoia, and no ears".<sup>5</sup>  "Chopper is twisted around the wrong way. His friends are his enemies. His crimes are his achievements. The price on his head measures his worth. He claims that 'drugs ruined the criminal world,' but he enjoys a little speed up the snout..." He repeatedly stabs men, showing eerie remorse. "Fuck, shit, are you OK? Are you alright?" Holding their necks together, dying in a pool of blood, Chopper asks whether they'd like a cigarette. "Quite the gentlemen." The film "jeopardizes the viewer's sense of security and challenges values set" by Australian society.<sup>6</sup></p>
                        <hr align="left" size="1">
                        <p><small>
                            <ul>
                                <li>5. <a href="http://metro.sandiegometro.com/reel/index.php?reelID=207" target="_blank">Jean Lowerison, Chopper, (2000)</a>.</li>
                                <li>6. <a href="http://www.infilm.com.au/reviews/chopper.htm" target="_blank">Luke Buckmaster, Chopper, (2000)</a>.</li>
                            </ul>
                            </small></p>
                        <p>&nbsp;</p>
                        <p>Without the violence or brutality, the film would ring untrue, turn into an after-school special, and completely miss its target audience. "Chopper," while violent, has a humor to it. The unbelievable events that may or may not be embellished make ninety percent of the film bearable. The last five to ten minutes of the film bring the whole story together. Chopper sits alone in his gaol cell, watching himself on television. Chopper ends up alone because of the life he chose. </p>
                        <p>Because of how the violence is depicted in "Chopper," the message is often lost. You see everything. You become desensitized to the violence. "City of God" does a much better job of depicting the violence by not actually showing it. The violence is much more powerful when left up to the imagination of the audience.  To reach the young audience, "Boyz 'R' Us" needs to draw inspiration from films like "City of God," which show less and leave the violence up to the imagination. The use of humor or light relief in "Chopper" should also influence "Boyz 'R' Us."</p>
                         </div>
                </div>
            </div>
